The original length of the side of the triangle parallel to the x-axis can be found using the Pythagorean theorem:

$$
\begin{aligned}
L &= \sqrt{800^2 + 800^2} \\
&= \sqrt{640000 + 640000} \\
&= \sqrt{1280000} \\
&= 1131.86 \text{ mm}
\end{aligned}
$$

The change in length of the side of the triangle parallel to the x-axis is given as 5 mm.

Therefore, the average normal strain $\varepsilon_x$ is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\varepsilon_x &= \frac{\Delta L}{L} \\
&= \frac{5}{1131.86} \\
&= 0.00443 \text{ mm/mm}
\end{aligned}
$$

